post_text:
I wanted to share some exciting news. The USDA just extended a waiver for CNS to provide free meals to ALL students until December 31st, 2020. That means for meal distribution at OK & PEC and then when we return to in-person learning, all students will be able to come through the lunch line and receive free meals.

No paperwork needed, and no checking out at the point of service with pin numbers or IDs (we will simply bee tallying student meals). This will allow us to provide the safest and contact-free meal service possible. It will also help speed up the lunch line, which I know has been a concern. I will send out more details about the meal service for reopening as we get closer.

Lea Bonelli, MS, RD
Director of Child Nutrition Services
Encinitas Union School District

This will allow us to provide the safest and contact-free meal service possible. It will also help speed up the lunch line, which I know has been a concern. EUSD Families,
ASPIRE REGISTRATION OPENS Thursday, August 20 at 9:00 AM *Priority registration will be given to essential workers through Friday at 3:00 PM.

2. Registration Form can be found at www.eusd.net/enrichment and e-mailed to Aspire.Registration@eusd.net
3. Hard copy registration forms available at the EUSD District Office located at 101 S. Rancho Santa Fe Road, Encinitas, CA 92024

shared_text:
EUSD Farm Lab
August 4 at 3:43 PM ·

It's tomato time at FarmLab! We're in peak harvest season, bringing in tomatoes from the field to become future pizza sauce. These tomatoes are picked at peak ripeness, and therefore peak sweetness and peak nutrition!

Conventional tomatoes top the Dirty Dozen Food list with some of the highest concentrations of pesticides. But here at FarmLab we grow everything small scale, by hand, and with local compost and organic fertilizer. We use zero pesticides or herbicides (organic or otherwise) because we rely on building healthy soil to grow healthy plants. By growing this way we ensure our kids are getting only what they need: nutrients.
text:
EUSD Farm Lab
August 4 at 3:43 PM ·

It's tomato time at FarmLab! We're in peak harvest season, bringing in tomatoes from the field to become future pizza sauce. These tomatoes are picked at peak ripeness, and therefore peak sweetness and peak nutrition!

Conventional tomatoes top the Dirty Dozen Food list with some of the highest concentrations of pesticides. But here at FarmLab we grow everything small scale, by hand, and with local compost and organic fertilizer. We use zero pesticides or herbicides (organic or otherwise) because we rely on building healthy soil to grow healthy plants. By growing this way we ensure our kids are getting only what they need: nutrients.

shared_text:
SWPPP Internship
June 16 at 10:37 AM ·

Delivery of Certificates of Special Congressional Recognition from U.S. Representative from the 49th District, Mike Levin’s office.

These two Ocean Knoll 5th grade students and their SWPPP Instructor @jamieg222 , were recognized for their work and their presentation to the Solana Beach Eco Rotary Club. The presentation showed the significant environmental work they had completed at their school. This included storm drain maintenance, irrigation evaluation and recommendations, concluding with a construction project they designed and supervised in collaboration with EUSD Facilities & Grounds crew. This project eliminated a significant amount of sediment that flowed into the school parking lot and into a storm drain. The 45 attendees of the Rotary zoom meeting, were very impressed.

Paul Ecke Central is in Encinitas, California.
June 5 at 1:23 PM · Encinitas, CA ·

#repost from our friends at @leucadia101mainstreet ... Mark your calendar for LeucadiAID 2020 on Friday, June 26th: an at-home live concert event and fundraiser for Leucadia 101 🤍
Leucadia 101 Mainstreet relies on grants, income from events, and the generosity of the community in order to support local businesses and ensure the ongoing vitality of the 101 corridor in Leucadia. We’re not gonna lie to you: COVID-19 has eliminated opportunities for grants (for now) as municipalities grapple with their own challenges, and our beloved annual events like Taste of Leucadia, Summer Fun on the 101 and LeucadiART Walk will not be the same in 2020 as they have been in past years.
However, ever scrappy, we are bringing you a different way to celebrate the beginning of summer, support our local businesses, and enjoy some awesome summer tunes. Presenting LeucadiAID 2020: "Keep Small Strong"
Swipe through for how to participate & a special thank you to @dwellsfargo for designing these event graphics for us on the fly 🙌🏽 #leucadiAID #keepsmallstrong @ Encinitas, California

La Costa Heights Principal
June 4 at 5:53 PM ·

Hello LCH! I've heard there is a bit of confusion about the childcare situation for next school year after today's webinar. I'd like to clarify!

If we are in a position to need to implement the hybrid model next school year, we WILL be offering Aspire childcare for families on students' off-campus days. The childcare planning committee is working on developing plans and anticipates sending out a parent survey in the next week or two with information and collecting information.

I think the confusion might have come from the information about summer Aspire. Typically we have childcare through Aspire in the summer. However, because the health guidelines continue to keep schools closed at this time, we aren't offering any in-person programs this summer. Our EL Summer Academy and Extended School Year programs will be held via distance learning. And, we will not be offering summer Aspire childcare.

I hope that helps to clarify!

shared_text:
La Costa Heights Principal
May 14 at 3:00 PM ·

I am delighted to announce Amy Tuvo as LCH's Volunteer of the Year!

Amy is the person you want on your team, exemplifying what makes LCH so special! She has worn every possible hat - room parent, classroom volunteer, field trip driver, winter carnival, CRV recycling program, art show, book fair, jog-a-thon, kinder socials, strawberry sales, PTA board….the list goes on and on.

Amy steps in to help staff and families at a moment’s notice, just because she’s that kind of person. When you meet Amy you are instantly put at ease and simultaneously inspired because of her infectious personality and genuine spirit. Amy hasn’t missed a beat, continuing to support our school and our students, all the way through our school closures.

Thank you, Amy - for you! LCH has been so fortunate to have you as part of our family! We will miss you after this year!

Hello EUSD Families!

WHERE WE ARE AT NOW:
Currently over 500 EUSD students and their families are experiencing food insecurity and are receiving hot lunches and breakfasts from EUSD at Ocean Knoll Elementary on Mondays and Wednesdays. As of this week, we will have given out around 4,500 Bags of Food, 700 Smart & Final Gift Cards, and 1300 Loaves of Bread. We have raised $80,000!

Rob Machado
April 14 at 1:32 PM ·

Hey everyone, the 50th anniversary of Earth Day is coming up on April 22nd. And while we’re all hunkered down at home, I want to hear about the positive choices you’re making to help keep Mother Earth healthy like avoiding single-use plastic water bottles, composting and planting a garden, etc. We’re asking YOU to share your climate action at home to help inspire and educate each other during Earth month! To participate, share your ideas by posting a photo or video and TAG @robmachadofoundation and #climateactionathome. On #EarthDay, I’m going to pick my favorite submission and the WINNER will get a virtual phone hang with me!

Stay healthy all and let’s continue to work together to keep the earth healthy too. 🤙🏼🌎

shared_text:
La Costa Heights Principal
April 6 at 1:08 PM ·

I went again today to collect donations and distribution groceries (and gift cards) to families in need here in our community. The rain waited, fortunately, until families had come and gone. My heart aches and is warmed by both the need and the generosity in our community.

Grateful tears and sighs of relief came from parents, particularly with the receipt of the gift cards (thank you to EEF)! We distributed approximately 190 $50 gift cards (one per family) for basic needs today. Truly remarkable!

Diapers and basic food needs continue to be a huge need! If you would like to contribute, please let me know. We will continue to do this work each Monday and Wednesday for as long as we have donations and volunteers during this time of need.

Now, I’m home, drinking a cup of tea to warm up...about ready to dive into my email. I know how incredibly blessed I am though all of this. And I know that together we can take care of all of our community!

E-FLYER #CLIMATEACTIONATHOME CHALLENGE WITH ROB MACHADO FOUNDATION

#CLIMATEACTIONATHOME INSTAGRAM POST
While we’re all at home to help keep everyone healthy, we want to hear about positive choices you’re making to help keep Mother Earth healthy.

Post a video or photo with #climateactionathome. Rob Machado is going to pick his favorite one on Earth Day and the winner will receive a video call with Rob so you can personally show him all your climate actions at home live on video.

Follow @robmachadofoundation and use the #climateactionathome to participate in this challenge to celebrate Earth Day.

Please see the fire for information: http://www.eusd.net/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/climateactionathome-e-flyer.pdf

post_text:
From Encinitas Union School District's EEF:
We are blown away by all of the PTA support and the enthusiasm from the community with the donations that are coming in. To date, TOGETHER, we have raised 27k! This week we plan to distribute $15k in $50 gift cards to Smart and Final to families participating in the Grab & Go program. In addition to the Smart and Final gift cards, we have been fortunate enough to find a local EUSD family who is a wholesale food distributor. They have generously offered to donate some food items as well as sell some to us at cost. We will be looking to use some of the raised Be Strong/Se Fuerte funds to purchase additional food items to add to our Grab & Go, for our vulnerable families. In addition we are looking at getting all of the donations matched with grant opportunities.

All EUSD schools and the District Office will be closed
to the public for Spring Break from March 30 – April 10,
2020. Following Spring Break, the District will be
closed indefinitely due to the current health situation.
Please visit www.eusd.net for the most up-to-date
information.
REGISTRATION IS ONLINE AT WWW.EUSD.NET
For assistance contact Amy León at
Amy.Leon@eusd.net or 760-944-4300, ext. 1161
